{{distinguish|Colin Clark (economist)}} '''Colin Whitcomb Clark''' (born 1931) is a Professor Emeritus of Mathematics at [[University of British Columbia|The University of British Columbia]]. Clark specializes in [[behavioral ecology]] and the economics of natural resources, specifically, in the management of commercial fisheries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.math.ubc.ca/~cytryn/MathBio/clark.php|title=Mathematical Biology at UBC|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=November 19, 2016}}</ref> Clark was named a Fellow of the International Institute of Fisheries Economics & Trade (IIFET) in 2016 for his contributions to [[Bioeconomics (fisheries)|bioeconomics]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://oregonstate.edu/dept/IIFET/PressRelease2016IIFETFellowsClark.pdf|title=International Institute of Fisheries Economics & Trade Names Colin Clarke IIFET 2016 Fellow|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=|via=}}</ref> Clark's impact upon fisheries economics through his scholarly work is encapsulated in ''Mathematical Bioeconomics: The Mathematics of Conservation,'' which is considered to be a classic contribution in [[Environmental economics|environmental economic]] theory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Munro|first=Gordon R.|last2=Sumaila|first2=U. Rashid|date=2015-04-25|title=On the Contributions of Colin Clark to Fisheries Economics|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10640-015-9910-4|journal=Environmental and Resource Economics|language=en|volume=61|issue=1|pages=1–17|doi=10.1007/s10640-015-9910-4|issn=0924-6460}}</ref>
==Honours and awards== *1997 Elected [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] <ref> {{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/colin-clark-11227/|title=Colin Clark - Biography|publisher= Royal Society|accessdate= 20 February 2017}} </ref>
